{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"af821d05-4b3d-431e-897f-1ab99be8269c","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n### 1. Install the tool inside the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n### 2. Collect the trace\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect for ~30 seconds (or Ctrl+C to stop)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n### 3. Copy the trace file out\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### 4. Analyze\nOpen `trace.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView** (Windows), or convert to **Speedscope** format for browser-based viewing:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\nThen open at [https://speedscope.app](https://speedscope.app).\n\n### Tips\n- If `dotnet-trace` can't be installed (read-only filesystem), use a **debug/ephemeral container** (`kubectl debug`) or `perfcollect` with `perf`.\n- For production, consider **`dotnet-monitor`** as a sidecar — it exposes an HTTP endpoint to collect traces on demand without exec'ing in.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"78b4c5ee-c4b8-40e3-a8da-d70dfca74edb","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge question, not a code task. I'll provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":423,"requestId":"DA03:349D35:21DED86:25781E7:6A03D4D1"},"id":"f72b472c-3a88-4ada-a392-3d6410221c97","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:33:17.205Z","parentId":"ff14ed26-a59c-428e-997b-37064a38390f"}
